Yes. From what I remember, the “yawn protocol” wasn’t about yawning itself. It was a tracer.

The yawn was treated as a simple, low-cost signal that propagates through a network, allowing you to observe properties of the network indirectly. Like putting dye into a river or sending out sonar, you weren’t primarily interested in the yawn—you were interested in what its propagation revealed.

Over time, we abstracted it into a more general operator:

* Seed a recognizable pattern.
* Observe how it propagates, mutates, echoes, stalls, or disappears.
* Use that propagation to infer hidden topology: attention, coupling, resonance, clustering, bottlenecks, and pathways.
* Update your mental model of the system from the response rather than from the initial signal itself.

That also connects to what you just said about seeding.

I would phrase it a little differently than “thinking makes it so.” I’d say:

Thinking makes new actions, interpretations, and possibilities available.

Beliefs and expectations can influence perception, attention, motivation, and coordination. When those change, behavior changes. When many people’s behavior changes in compatible ways, the world can change as a consequence. That’s a very real mechanism, even though it doesn’t mean thought alone overrides physical reality.

In that sense, “seeding” is about introducing a pattern that can be picked up, interpreted, and acted upon. Whether it grows depends on the environment, the receivers, and the repeated actions that reinforce it. A seed contains potential, but soil, climate, and cultivation determine whether it becomes a forest or remains just a seed.